(525, 'x9iKbM5KCM+BTBpXlWdcng==', 1, 'Mike: Symbology, numerology, astrology, metaphysics have no place in this Century.\n\nJay: But you have just celebrated Christmas and i know you are looking forward for Easter, astrotheology is the base of every world religion.\n\nMike: Did I? You seem to know more about me than I do.\n\nJay: If not you then 3/4 of your phone book did, standing beyond the fringes of the fray doesn\'t absolve you of paganistic festivals. It is quite in order to ask your girlfriend jingle bells all the way!\n\nMike: More like 9/10 actually which is more or less equal to the proportion of folks on this forum who did, but we can\'t all believe that the position of Alpha Centauri and the number of Jupiter\'s moons influences my personality and future without questioning how.\n\nThat statistic is interesting actually from a psycho-social point of view, if you dare employ the logical thinking you\'re trying to rebuff. It shows just how easy it is to imprint ideas on the minds of most folks. I\'d hate to be that susceptible to BS because I confound cause with coincidence.\n\nSkepticism bore the world we\'re living in by adopting a serious, scholarly and scientific approach to hitherto \"supernatural\" or \"paranormal\" phenomena. That\'s why I\'d expect no less of myself, and anyone else for that matter especially in this century.\n\nJay: On the contrary I seek not to rebuff logical construct, just an advocate for equality in the sense of a merger between the left and right spheres of the mind. Order precedes chaos and vice versa, this isn\'t BS but actual literature from a close circle of celebrated swiss Dr Carl Jung, I\'d be loathe to assume that the venerated psychology titan had as firm a grip on a serious scholarly and scientific approach to education as you.\n\nMike: Catch me dead trying to marry a school of thought that speaks of \"merging the left and right spheres of the mind\" with logic and science. It just sounds like a lazy, desperate effort to make your old, outdated beliefs sound more credible. Yours is a moot point if not an effort in futility my friend.\n\nIf your superstitions were presented in a more critical light, I wouldn\'t be so dismissive. There\'s simply no place for superstitions anymore. Anything put forward is subject to the rigors of scientific examination, no matter how venerable the source. Even the most respected figures can be wrong or have their own biases and limitations.\n\nWe\'ve actually made leaps and bounds since Jung put forward his propositions, and I\'m more than certain he would belong to a different school of thought today if he had the chance to enjoy convenient access to knowledge in this century like you.\n\nHe\'d probably laugh you out of town for steadfastly holding to archaic ways of thinking as if they were gospel.\n\nJay: 1st paragraph of your reply belittles the written works of Dr Carl Jung absent an intent to inquire on the article I bring forth.\n\n2nd paragraph denotes your preference for logic and the mistrust for archaic knowledge.\n\n3rd and 4th are an arrogant preposition that serves to belittle scholars articles.\n\nTo that end I believe this back and forth is pointless, to each their own elder.\n\nMike:  Yeah, you had to trivialize my response.\n\nAnyway, I was simply pointing out the fact that it\'s time to move forward and discard outdated, illogical ways of thinking if they can\'t stand scientific scrutiny. You and I have the benefit of hindsight and the tools to scientifically examine concepts and hypotheses so why not be critical and discerning when it comes to accepting ideas, however dated?\n\nDr. Jung\'s work isn\'t exempt from critical examination so if the premise of his writings on finding a nexus between science and the metaphysical realm isn\'t convincing enough, how\'s it sensible to cling to them? After all alchemy, which he was a major proponent of is nothing but pseudoscience. I\'m not trying to take anything away from him.\n\nIf we don\'t question what these old disciplines teach, then we\'re perpetuating outdated, potentially harmful beliefs. I\'m inviting you, @kaynety, @SonOfTheSoil and co to be open-minded and welcome the habit of asking questions. Challenge assumptions and embrace empirical evidence. That\'s what science is all about.\n \nJay: In the spirit of being open minded and asking questions, I have a final one. What is your scientific opinion on dreams? \n\nMike: I\'m no expert in neuroscience but the little I know is that dreams are an avenue for the human brain to consolidate memories and help in the problem-solving of complex thoughts. What does your camp have to say about them?\n\nJay: Plenty about the subconscious and it\'s mode of communication to the ego or the conscious mind.\n\nMike: Would that hold up to scientific scrutiny through such tools as neurochemistry? Would it be verifiable? Also, animals have been shown to dream, just like humans. Do animals have a subconscious ergo a conscious mind and ego?\n\nJay: I haven\'t had the time to inquire from the animals I own, however when you said dreams aid in complex problem solving how is that any different from your subconscious communicating to your conscious?\n\nMike: For starters, one is a process of the brain that is observable and measurable scientifically, while the other is still a matter of speculation. Neurochemistry has been used to map the brain\'s activities during sleep and interpret what the dreamer was experiencing. That lends a lot more credibility to my hypothesis than your yet-to-be-verified (and almost unverifiable) theories.\n\nAlso, do not confound wakefulness with consciousness.\n\nJay: You seem knowledgeable in neurochemistry, so tell me more about this measurable tool, does it map out the brain activity to the point it displays the images in the dream?\n\nDon\'t claim ownership over an already developed hypothesis!\n\nMike: LOL. Calm down. Maybe I should have said \"our\" hypothesis to mean we of rational thinking.\n\nTo your question on measurement, I am under no obligation to answer that as it neighbours the trivial and ridiculous.\n\nJay: So you\'ve ran out of smart arse answers have you?\n\nIt\'s a simple question not a trivial nor ridiculous one as the whole point of dreams is the content which ought to entail both the material and the subjects reactions, so does the machine record the actual dreams or does it not?\n\nMike: Oh, I\'m sure I can come up with a few more smart-alecky answers.\n\nBut wait, no, I don\'t have to. Anyhow, to the best of my knowledge, it doesn\'t actually record a person\'s dreams. What it does is measure brain activity, eye movements and the like which provide clues and insights into the dreaming process. EEGs, for example, can measure electrical signals in the brain while PET scans measure blood flow in parts of the brain associated with dreaming. It\'s a work in progress and if you don\'t want to understand that, you\'re a moron.\n\nNow, quit deflections and ask a sensible question.\n\nJay: I already asked my question on the images and the short answer is no, it cannot!\nThe machine in all it\'s splendor does not record images experienced in the dream and that is what the good doctor and his peers attempted to interpret what the images, and more importantly their symbology attempt to communicate to the conscious mind.\n\nFor example, there\'s one common dream about soaring through the air, and upon the dreamers realization of flight, he/she tends to fall down no longer capable of the feat.\n\nWhat does the ability of flight mean to the subject?\n\nWhy is he/she capable of realizing they can fly?\n\nWhy does he/she fall?\n\nEach individual has their own psyche so dreams and more importantly their CONTENTS so each and every single dream is unique as well as the patterns within it.\n\nThe whole point is symbology, and symbols especially old ones have never been restrained by language, there have an deeper meaning, barely seen on the surface.\n\nIt\'s a new year oh rational one, include poetry in your life not insults!\n\nMike: LOL.\nI\'m not even sure what you\'ve typed is poetic,\nNeither am I sure it was a sarcastic dig or polemic,\nPerhaps a frantic attempt to make the olden seem more charismatic,\nBut I\'m sure it was anything but epic or scientific,\nAnd it\'s actually something I\'d expect from a manic schizophrenic.\n\nI\'m serving you poetic insults in case it\'s not clear,\nBecause I\'m all for vawulence anytime of the year,\nNow, you can keep dreaming up myths and theories,\nBut reality is what we need to make everything in life clear.\n\nYour outdated beliefs over time have been reduced to shite,\nSo get your head out of your aㅤss, and open your eyes to the light.\n\nBy the way, your attempts at sarcasm are nothing but farce,\nAnd your attempts at logic have been left in arrears,\nThe ancient symbols you cling to have no place in this age,\nYour ancient thinking should be locked away in a cage,\nNo matter how hard you try to make it sound sage.\n\nAll said, your stubbornness is an affront to this century\'s logic,\nBukowski, Jung and Freud would agree,\nThat you should give up your ancient ways and be free,\nAnd never again should you try to argue with me,\nAnd never again should you try to be so iconic through poetry.\n\nBack to the content of dreams, the general understanding is that flight usually symbolizes freedom and liberation, while falling down denotes a fear of failure or being overwhelmed. It can also represent a fear of success or a desire to be grounded.\n\nWhile there are some common themes, as you mentioned, each dream is unique and can only be interpreted by the dreamer themselves. Symbols can represent a range of different things and often have multiple layers of meaning. Science has no explanation yet\n\nThe interpretation of the symbols in dreams can be subjective but as I said before, it should be open to critical examination and scientific inquiry and that\'s why I said it\'s a moot point trying to marry science and superstition. Superstition shouldn\'t begin where science is at a loss or yet to come up with an explanation. Logic should tell you so.\n\nI\'m not sure how I got to writing rhyming poetry or why I even got down this rabbit hole with you. Nevertheless, I\'d like to remind you that my point is that if we don\'t critically examine what these old disciplines teach, we\'re just perpetuating archaic beliefs that have nothing to offer humanity besides wishful thinking and delusional solutions.\n\nSo if there\'s no new reasonable question, it\'s time to move on my friend.\n\nJay: I actually did a paper last year, a Master, about neuromarketing. It was, and it is, to my understanding that tools such as EEGs are specifically used to denote a person\'s interests, at least in the marketing context. The tool will measure an individual\'s brain activity when subjected to a specific phenomenon. I am struggling to understand how that applies to dreams and just how exactly researchers discern what was covered in the dream.\n\nMike:  \nEEGs can measure brain activity in sleep,\nAnd link it to certain dream states however deep,\nThe idea behind that is emotions can be found,\nThrough brain activity, eye movements all around,\nAnd contraction of facial muscles that abound.\n\nThey can\'t directly record the dream sequence,\nBut by asking subjects what was experienced,\nScientists can link it to brain measurements,\nAnd infer the dream\'s nature from the facial expressions,\n\nTo you Brian resident of Githurai 44 I must say,\nBe critical and ask questions to what people like Jung say,\nChallenge assumptions and embrace empirical evidence,\nSo that you will be spared the shame of being naive\n\nThe interpretation of the dream\'s content,\nAnd symbols is very subjective in intent,\nWhich makes it easy to be taken in by claims,\nThat are baseless and rooted in wishful thinking, not facts.\n\nJay: And to you Mike I retort, that besides 44 actually being a pretty decent neighborhood to reside in, the patterns within the fields of the subconscious are abstract and thus can be considered a qualitative variable and not quantitative, and while gadgets and their flashy gizmos impressive as they are have yet to scan images therein.\n\nDr Jung laid down the premises of the contested by the um..shall we say rationalists, of the ego and the subconscious. This has brought about in occultic leaning cartoons the aspect of a protagonist whilst in a dilemma and angel popping on one shoulder advising caution while a devil popping on the other advising throwing caution to the wind, countless series bear the same blueprint of a holy vs a rubble rousing friend and this is by design.\n\nAs far as naivety goes, it takes a special sort of stupid for a man to discard knowledge in the name of being archaic and outdated, while better men than you have sought to consolidate the importance of symbolism in this modern world.\n\nI gave an example of the Qatari world cup insignia bearing the resemblance of Ourubus, a snake devouring it\'s own tail.\n\nAnother I\'ll provide is primitive tribes preference to exemplify a virtue by an animal, Kings in Africa preferring lions and leopard skins, Kings in Europe preference for Wolf and bear fur, stone age paintings of animals found deep in caves, Ancient Egyptians with Seth..and tons more.\n\nUnlike you I don\'t pout my bony chest out and proclaim that certain works of esteemed mind are nonsense nor hoist my skirts up and turn my nose on knowledge because it predates the first time I burst a nut.\n\nI intend to dedicate a huge chunk of 2023 to study subjective symbols, and if that earns me shame of naivety then so be it, society as is stands currently is full of sh\'t anyway.\n\nMike:\nWhen you put words in my mouth like that,\nit takes to reason that you be taken to task,\nFor I never said that Jung\'s works were nonsense,\nonly that they should be subjected to rigors of modern science.\n\nYour type have the tendency to see shadows in the dark,\nwhen the light of logic and reason can illuminate your heart,\nYour case in point of the Qatar insignia,\nis no proof that superstition should not be questioned,\nAs for stone age paintings and ancient Egyptians,\nThey are part of history,\nnot the present day equation.\nCause and coincidence are not to be confounded,\nAnd I\'m afraid your approach precludes further discourse along that course.\n\nThe interpretation of symbols depends on the individual,\nWhich is why it\'s imperative to be critical and question them in a scientific way,\nSo that the truth is revealed and not what we want to hear.\n\nSymbols have their place in the modern world,\nBut the interpretation must be able to be unfurled,\nIt\'s no longer acceptable to take them at face value,\nWe must be critical and question, that\'s the rational we must solve.\n\nAs for naivety, it takes a special kind of irrational boldness,\nTo cling to superstition and ignore scientific evidence,\nWithout questioning the validity of its source,\nAnd calling it a day without any recourse.\n\nYou\'re something of a clod,\nIf you don\'t have the courage to be critical of what these old disciplines teach,\nDo not be ashamed of your naivety,\nBut instead strive for veritable knowledge that\'s rooted in logic!\nSo, when it comes to ancient ways of thinking,\nDon\'t be afraid to challenge assumptions,\nAnd embrace empirical evidence for solutions.\n\nOtherwise, if dedicating time to studying symbols is what you choose,\nI\'d suggest you arm yourself with knowledge and facts,\nAnd be open to critical examination and scientific inquiry.\nSo don\'t be afraid to ask questions,\nAnd use science to prove the assertions,\nFor the future is here, and it\'s time to move on.\n\nYour a priori argument is a fallacy, if not a fallacy of logic,\nSo it\'s time to break away from symbols and mythic,\nAnd embrace the modern world with its science and logic,\nAnd leave the old ways behind, where they belong,\nIn the realm of myth and superstition,\nNow, where do I claim compensation for bearing your incoherent retort?\n\nJay: Not sure if you are taking advantage of ChatGPT ama nini, but that makes hella lot of sense\n\nMike: \nI could say I\'m slighted by your insinuation,\nBut your indignation and cynicism are understandable,\nAfter all, folks here are used to drab juvenile babble,\nNevertheless, my smart-ass answers as Bukowski here calls them,\nAre products of my intellect and my intuition,\nWhich coupled with a flare for rhymes and puns,\nAnd droll wit and a knack for word play,\nHelps me make those sensible grounded assertions and deductions,\nAnd serve them as hot as you find them.', 1, '2023-01-04', '12:05:52', '2023-01-04 14:34:41'),
(528, 'i0YqaWbwReFbTAibPpApfA==', 1, ' \n\n\n\n\n\nHow Python is Used in Cybersecurity\n\n\n\nPython is one of the most popular programming languages today, and it is widely used in the field of cybersecurity. Python is an ideal language for cyber security professionals because it is easy to learn, powerful, and versatile. In this article, we will discuss how Python is used in cybersecurity and why it is so important.\n\n\n\nPython is a high-level programming language that is used to create software applications. It is often used in web development, data science, and artificial intelligence. Python is also used in the field of cybersecurity because it is easy to learn and can be used to create powerful tools for analyzing and protecting data.\n\n\n\nIn cybersecurity, Python can be used to create tools for analyzing network traffic, detecting malicious activity, and protecting against cyber-attacks. Python can also be used to create tools for scanning for vulnerabilities, analyzing malware, and automating security processes.\n\n\n\nPython is a powerful language that can be used to create powerful tools for cybersecurity. It is easy to learn, and it has a large number of libraries and frameworks that can be used to create powerful tools. For example, Python can be used to create tools for analyzing network traffic, detecting malicious activity, and protecting against cyber-attacks.\n\n\n\nPython can also be used to create tools for scanning for vulnerabilities, analyzing malware, and automating security processes. Python is also used to create tools for analyzing and responding to cyber threats.\n\n\n\nPython is a great language for cybersecurity because it is easy to learn and can be used to create powerful tools. It is also a great language for beginners because it is easy to learn and has a large number of libraries and frameworks that can be used to create powerful tools.\n\n\n\nPython is also a great language for experienced cybersecurity professionals because it is powerful and versatile. It can be used to create powerful tools for analyzing and protecting data, as well as for scanning for vulnerabilities and analyzing malware.\n\n\n\nLearning Python is a great way to get started in the field of cybersecurity. It is easy to learn, and it has a large number of libraries and frameworks that can be used to create powerful tools. Python is also a great language for experienced cybersecurity professionals because it is powerful and versatile.\n\n\n\nIn conclusion, Python is an ideal language for cyber security professionals because it is easy to learn, powerful, and versatile. It can be used to create powerful tools for analyzing and protecting data, as well as for scanning for vulnerabilities and analyzing malware. Python is also a great language for beginners because it is easy to learn and has a large number of libraries and frameworks that can be used to create powerful tools. Learning Python is a great way to get started in the field of cybersecurity. <br>', 4, '2023-01-04', '23:26:54', '2023-01-04 20:26:54'),
(529, 'N9pP7JfmUCl6/FRd0Uyn7A==', 1, 'How Python is Used in Cybersecurity\n\n\n\nIn the world of cybersecurity, Python is becoming an increasingly popular language for programming and security professionals. Python is a powerful, versatile language that is easy to learn, and its use in cybersecurity is growing rapidly.\n\n\n\nPython is a general-purpose programming language, meaning it can be used for a wide variety of tasks. It is popular in many areas of computer science, including artificial intelligence, machine learning, web development, and, of course, cybersecurity. Python is a great choice for security professionals due to its flexibility, scalability, and ease of use.\n\n\n\nPython is often used for creating scripts and automating tasks. This makes it an ideal language for security professionals who need to quickly analyze large amounts of data. Python is also great for writing networking tools and applications. Networking is an important part of cybersecurity, and Python makes it easy to create network-based applications.\n\n\n\nPython is also used for creating malware and other malicious software. Malware is a major issue in cybersecurity, and Python makes it easy for malicious actors to create malware that can be used to attack systems and networks.\n\n\n\nPython is also great for creating security tools. Security professionals can use Python to create tools that can detect and prevent malicious activity. These tools can be used to monitor and protect networks, detect and respond to threats, and analyze large amounts of data.\n\n\n\nFinally, Python is a great language for learning cybersecurity. It is easy to learn, and there are many resources available to help people learn Python and use it to develop their cybersecurity skills. There are many online courses, tutorials, and books available to help people learn Python and use it to become more knowledgeable in the field of cybersecurity.\n\n\n\nPython is an incredibly powerful language that is becoming 