(562, 'Y0yNDWwCVZ9/3UkBaaQhNg==', 161, 'You are a front-end web development and SEO writing expert. You are required to write a factual, interesting and informative comparison article named \"ID vs Class in CSS: Differences Between Selectors\" for a tech blog.<br><br><div>Use tech review jargon related to CSS and front-end web development, and make the article as interesting as possible.</div><div><br></div><div>Avoid repeating the same words and phrases, and use a variety of sentence structures.    <br><br>Incorporate human-like language and style (use contractions like â€œdonâ€™tâ€ and â€œcanâ€™tâ€, transitional phrasing to move from one idea to the next, use idioms and colloquialisms, tech reviews jargon, and terminology related to CSS and web development)<br></div><br>Structure of the article:<br><br>â— Introduction - (2 juicy and well-thought paragraphs)<br>â— ID vs Class in CSS: Side-by-Side Comparison (a bullet point list of all areas in which ID and Class can be compared - you will use the list in the next section)<br>â— ID vs Class in CSS: Whatâ€™s the Difference? (Discuss the differences listed above, each with it\'s own short subheading and explanation)<br>â— ID vs Class in CSS: 5 Must-Know Facts - Describe 10 facts and trivia related to the CSS selectors, which aren\'t discussed before in the article<br>â— ID vs Class in CSS: Which One Is Better? Which One Should You Choose? - 3 detailed paragraphs<br>â— ID vs Class in CSS: Key Differences and Full Comparison FAQs (Frequently Asked Questions) - 6 FAQs about things not already discussed in the article<br><br>Use diverse sources for your information including the following:<br><br>[1] The difference between IDs and classes is that the first one is unique, and the second one is not. This means that each element can have only one ID, and each page can have only one element with this ID. When using the same ID on multiple elements, the code wont pass validation.<br><br>URL: https://www.w3docs.com/learn-css/css-id-and-class.html<br><br>[2] In most cases, it is preferable to add a class to an element instead of an ID. However, if using the ID is the only way to target the element â€” perhaps because you do not have access to the markup and cannot edit it â€” this will work. Summary That wraps up Type, class, and ID selectors.<br><br>URL: https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Learn/CSS/Building_blocks/Selectors/Type_Class_and_ID_Selectors<br><br>[3] In CSS, id s look like #elementID and class elements look like .someClass In general, use id whenever you want to refer to a specific element and class when you have a number of things that are all alike. For instance, common id elements are things like header, footer, sidebar. Common class elements are things like highlight or external-link.<br><br>URL: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/544010/whats-the-difference-between-an-id-and-a-class<br><br>[4] This is much like IDs and Classes. Information that is reusable should be kept in a class and information that is totally unique should be kept in an ID. IDs have special browser functionality Classes have no special abilities in the browser, but IDs do have one very important trick up their sleeve. This is the hash value in the URL.<br><br>URL: https://css-tricks.com/the-difference-between-id-and-class/<br><br>[5] When comparing CSS class vs ID, the difference is that CSS class applies a style to multiple elements. ID, on the other hand, applies a style to one unique element. ID is also special in that you can use a special URL to link directly to an element and its used by JavaScript.<br><br>URL: https://careerkarma.com/blog/css-class-vs-id-2/<br><br>[6] Classes are useful when you have, or possibly will have in the future, more than one element that shares the same style. An example may be a div of comments or a certain list style to use for related links. Additionally, a given element can have more than one class associated with it, while an element can only have one id.<br><br>URL: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/12889362/what-is-the-difference-between-id-and-class-in-css-and-when-should-i-use-them<br><br>[7] Class and ID are selectors used to organize CSS code. ID describes something singular. Class describes something with multiple elements. While they work similarly, knowing when to use each can make your code cleaner. When creating a website, it is crucial to have a unified style throughout the page.<br><br>URL: https://www.bestcolleges.com/bootcamps/guides/css-class-vs-id/<br><br>[8] Id and class both are the CSS element selectors and are used to identify an element based on its assigned name. CSS id and class selectors are the most used selectors in CSS. During the use of selectors, sometimes there is confusion occurs between id and class.<br><br>URL: https://www.javatpoint.com/css-class-vs-id<br><br>[9] .class will affect elements matching value in class attribute. style by id will affect elements matching value in id attribute. it is recommended that you do not repeat ID value in elements, since that is suppose to be unique identifier of element on current page. Share Improve this answer Follow answered Jun 9, 2009 at 15:25 Andrija<br><br>URL: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/970730/css-id-vs-class<br><br>[10] A period (.) indicates a class, and a hash ( #) indicates an ID. The fundamental difference between is that you can reuse a class on your page over and over, whereas an ID can be used once. That is, of course, if you are sticking to WC3 standards.<br><br>URL: https://stackoverflow.com/questions/602168/in-css-what-is-the-difference-between-and-when-declaring-a-set-of-styles<br><br>', 1, '2023-02-25', '15:06:09', '2023-02-25 12:03:57'),
(565, 'Rzd/rIyzejY3GosxeDMiAA==', 161, '<b>Literary devices</b> are techniques used in writing to convey a deeper meaning that goes beyond what is written on the page. They are used to create strong, distinctive, and believable characters and to prompt reflection on life, society, and what it means to be human. Examples of literary devices include alliteration, metaphor, simile, analogy, imagery, symbolism, personification, hyperbole, irony, juxtaposition, paradox, allusion, allegory, ekphrasis, onomatopoeia, pun, repetition, dialogue, word play, and parallelism.<br><br>Example:<br>Original sentence:<br>She was so angry that she could feel her blood boiling.<br>Rewritten with different literary devices:<b><br>Alliteration</b>: She seethed with such fury that her blood boiled.<b><br>Metaphor</b>: Rage consumed her, turning her blood into a bubbling cauldron.<b><br>Simile</b>: Her anger was like a pot on the stove, the heat rising until it reached boiling point.<b><br>Imagery</b>: Her face was red as a tomato and her eyes blazed with fury, as if she would explode at any moment.<b><br>Personification</b>: Anger coursed through her veins, controlling her every move like a puppet master.<b><br>Hyperbole</b>: Her anger was so intense that it felt like her blood was about to boil over and flood the room.<b><br>Irony</b>: She laughed through gritted teeth, her blood boiling with a mixture of amusement and anger.<b><br>Juxtaposition</b>: She was as calm as the surface of a lake, but underneath, her blood was boiling with a fiery rage.<b><br>Allusion</b>: Her anger was like a scene from Dante\'s Inferno, with her blood boiling in the fiery depths of hell.<b><br>Onomatopoeia</b>: She gritted her teeth so hard that they made a grinding sound, her blood boiling with anger.', 1, '2023-02-26', '09:29:48', '2023-02-26 06:27:32'),
(571, 'WuOyU1CmyjbGk+hn4y4ixQ==', 161, 'Summarize the following into two detailed paragraphs:<br><br>Up to what cable distance can pcie 3.0 interface send data in meters?\n\nPCIe 3.0 is an interface  protocol that enables high-speed data communication between devices. It has a maximum transmission distance of up to 10 meters, depending on the type of cable used. The length of the cable will determine the speed and quality of the data transfer, as well as its maximum distance.\n\nFor example, CAT5e cables can reach up to 100m in length with a PCIe 3.0 connection, while CAT6 cables can reach up to 55m in length. However, using such long cables may result in signal degradation due to attenuation and crosstalk interference, which could lead to data loss or errors during transmission. Therefore, it is recommended that shorter cables be used for optimal performance and reliability when using PCIe 3.0 connections over longer distances.\n\nIn addition, it is important to note that PCIe 3.0 also supports copper-based cables, such as USB Type C and Thunderbolt 3 cables. These types of cables are typically limited to a maximum transmission distance of 2m due to their design and construction materials. However, they offer much higher speeds than traditional copper-based cables due to their improved signal integrity and reduced crosstalk interference levels.\n\nOverall, PCIe 3.0 can transmit data at distances up to 10 meters when using the correct type of cable for the application at hand. While longer distances may be possible with certain types of cables, it is important to consider factors such as signal degradation and crosstalk interference before making any decisions regarding cable lengths and transmission distances for PCIe 3.0 connections.<br><br>Up to what cable distance can pcie 4.0 interface send data in meters?<br>\nPCIe 4.0 is an interface protocol that enables high-speed  data communication between devices. It has a maximum transmission distance of up to 15 meters, depending on the type of cable used. The length of the cable will determine the speed and quality of the data transfer, as well as its maximum distance.\n\nFor example, CAT6a cables can reach up to 100m in length with a PCIe 4.0 connection, while CAT7 cables can reach up to 55m in length. However, using such long cables may result in signal degradation due to attenuation and crosstalk interference, which could lead to data loss or errors during transmission. Therefore, it is recommended that shorter cables be used for optimal performance and reliability when using PCIe 4.0 connections over longer distances.\n\nIn addition, it is important to note that PCIe 4.0 also supports fiber-optic cables for even greater distances and faster speeds than traditional copper-based cables are capable of providing. These types of cables are typically limited to a maximum transmission distance of 10km due to their design and construction materials. However, they offer much higher speeds than traditional copper-based cables due to their improved signal integrity and reduced crosstalk interference levels.\n\nOverall, PCIe 4.0 can transmit data at distances up to 15 meters when using the correct type of cable for the application at hand. While longer distances may be possible with certain types of cables such as fiber-optic ones, it is important to consider factors such as signal degradation and crosstalk interference before making any decisions regarding cable lengths and transmission distances for PCIe 4.0 connections.', 1, '2023-02-27', '19:24:37', '2023-02-27 16:22:15');
