(621, 'FuRkUu5VRR2My7YitShGgw==', 161, '<div>You are a computer and virtualization expert as well as an SEO expert. You are required to write a factual, interesting and informative 1500-word comparison article named \"VMWare vs VirtualBox: Full Virtual Machine Comparison\" for a tech blog.</div><br><div>Use tech review jargon and terminology related to computing and virtualization, and make the article as interesting as possible.</div><div><br></div><div>Avoid repeating the same words and phrases, and use a variety of sentence structures.    <br><br>Incorporate human-like language and style (use contractions like â€œdonâ€™tâ€ and â€œcanâ€™tâ€, transitional phrasing to move from one idea to the next, literary devices, a bit of humor, idioms and colloquialisms)<br></div><br>Structure of the article:<br><br>â— Introduction - (2 juicy and well-thought slightly humorous paragraphs)<br>â— VMWare vs VirtualBox: Side-by-Side Comparison (a bullet point list of all areas in which VMWare and VirtualBox can be compared - you will use the list in the next section)<br>â— VMWare vs VirtualBox: Whatâ€™s the Difference? (Discuss the differences listed above, each with it\'s own short subheading and detailed explanation)<br>â— VMWare vs VirtualBox: 5 Must-Know Facts - Describe 10 facts and trivia related to virtualization, virtualization applications, VMWare, and VirtualBox, which aren\'t discussed before in the article<br>â— VMWare vs VirtualBox: Which One Is Better? Which One Should You Use? - 3 detailed paragraphs<br>â— VMWare vs VirtualBox: Key Differences and Full Comparison FAQs (Frequently Asked Questions) - 10 FAQs about things not already discussed in the article<br>â— Conclusion - 2 juicy and well-thought paragraphs\n<br>\n\nIntroduction \n\nAre you  trying to decide between VMWare and VirtualBox for your virtualization needs? It can be a difficult decision, especially if youâ€™re not sure what the differences are between the two. Not to worry - weâ€™ve got you covered! In this article, weâ€™ll provide a side-by-side comparison of VMWare vs VirtualBox, so that you can make an informed decision about which one is best for you. Weâ€™ll also provide some interesting facts about virtualization, VMWare, and VirtualBox that will help you understand the nuances of each platform. So letâ€™s get started! \n\n\n\nVMWare vs VirtualBox: Side-by-Side Comparison \n\nâ€¢ Operating System Support: VMWare supports Windows 10, 8.1, 7, Vista and XP; while VirtualBox supports Windows 10/8/7/Vista/XP, Mac OS X 10.6 or later, Linux 2.6 or later and Solaris 11 or later \n\nâ€¢ Guest Operating Systems: VMWare supports Windows 10/8/7/Vista/XP; while VirtualBox supports Windows 95 through Windows 10 (32 bit &amp; 64 bit), Mac OS X 10.5 through macOS Mojave (64 bit), Linux 2.4 through 4.x (32 bit &amp; 64 bit) and OpenSolaris 2008 through Oracle Solaris 11 (32 bit &amp; 64 bit) \n# â€¢ CPU Architecture Support: VMWare supports x86 32-bit &amp; 64-bit; while VirtualBox supports x86 32-bit &amp; 64-bit as well as ARM  \nâ€¢ RAM Support: VMWare supports up to 32GB RAM; while VirtualBox supports up to 128GB RAM  \nâ€¢ Storage Capacity: VMWare supports up to 2TB storage capacity; while VirtualBox supports up to 16TB storage capacity  \nâ€¢ Networking Options: Both support bridged networking, NAT networking and host only networking  \nâ€¢ USB Device Connectivity: Both support USB 1.1 devices as well as USB 2.0 devices  \n\nVMWare vs VirtualBox: What\'s the Difference? \nOperating System Support \nThe main difference between VMWare and VirtualBox when it comes to operating system support is that VMWare only officially supports Windows systems whereas Virtualbox offers support for Mac OS X and Linux systems in addition to Windows systems. This means that if you want to use either platform on a non-Windows system then your only option is going to be Virtualbox. \n\nCPU Architecture Support \nAnother key difference between the two platforms is in terms of CPU architecture support - namely that VMWare only officially offers support for x86 CPUs whereas with Virtualbox you have the added benefit of being able to use ARM CPUs as well as x86 CPUs in your virtual machines. This makes it much easier for developers who need access to both types of architectures when working on their projects within a virtual environment since they don\'t have to switch back and forth between different platforms depending on their needs at any given time.  \n\n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;RAM Support\n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;When it comes to RAM support there is another significant difference between the two platforms - namely that VMWare\'s maximum supported RAM size is only 32GB whereas with Virtualbox you can go all the way up to 128GB RAM per machine if needed. This makes it much easier for developers who need access larger amounts of memory than what is available on most physical machines since they don\'t have to worry about running out of space when working on their projects within a virtual environment either due to hardware constraints or software limitations imposed by their chosen platform(s).\n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Storage Capacity\n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;The last major difference worth mentioning here when comparing VMWare vs Virtualbox in terms of storage capacity is that with VMWare the maximum supported storage size per machine is limited at 2TB whereas with Virtualbox this number goes all the way up 16TB which makes it much more suitable for large scale projects where large amounts of data need be stored securely within a single machine without having any issues related performance degradation due hardware constraints or software limitations imposed by their chosen platform(s).\n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Networking Options\n&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp;Both platforms offer similar networking options such as Bridged Networking, NAT Networking and Host Only Networking however there may be slight differences depending on which version of either platform you\'re using so m