(41, 1, '2023-01-04 09:17:24', '2023-01-04 09:17:24', '<div class=\"ql-editor\" data-gramm=\"false\" data-placeholder=\"Edit your post here\" contenteditable=\"true\"><p>Mike: Symbology, numerology, astrology, metaphysics have no place in this Century.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: But you have just celebrated Christmas and i know you are looking forward for Easter, astrotheology is the base of every world religion.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike: Did I? You seem to know more about me than I do.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: If not you then 3/4 of your phone book did, standing beyond the fringes of the fray doesn\'t absolve you of paganistic festivals. It is quite in order to ask your girlfriend jingle bells all the way!</p><p><br></p><p>Mike: More like 9/10 actually which is more or less equal to the proportion of folks on this forum who did, but we can\'t all believe that the position of Alpha Centauri and the number of Jupiter\'s moons influences my personality and future without questioning how.</p><p><br></p><p>That statistic is interesting actually from a psycho-social point of view, if you dare employ the logical thinking you\'re trying to rebuff. It shows just how easy it is to imprint ideas on the minds of most folks. I\'d hate to be that susceptible to BS because I confound cause with coincidence.</p><p><br></p><p>Skepticism bore the world we\'re living in by adopting a serious, scholarly and scientific approach to hitherto \"supernatural\" or \"paranormal\" phenomena. That\'s why I\'d expect no less of myself, and anyone else for that matter especially in this century.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: On the contrary I seek not to rebuff logical construct, just an advocate for equality in the sense of a merger between the left and right spheres of the mind. Order precedes chaos and vice versa, this isn\'t BS but actual literature from a close circle of celebrated swiss Dr Carl Jung, I\'d be loathe to assume that the venerated psychology titan had as firm a grip on a serious scholarly and scientific approach to education as you.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike: Catch me dead trying to marry a school of thought that speaks of \"merging the left and right spheres of the mind\" with logic and science. It just sounds like a lazy, desperate effort to make your old, outdated beliefs sound more credible. Yours is a moot point if not an effort in futility my friend.</p><p><br></p><p>If your superstitions were presented in a more critical light, I wouldn\'t be so dismissive. There\'s simply no place for superstitions anymore. Anything put forward is subject to the rigors of scientific examination, no matter how venerable the source. Even the most respected figures can be wrong or have their own biases and limitations.</p><p><br></p><p>We\'ve actually made leaps and bounds since Jung put forward his propositions, and I\'m more than certain he would belong to a different school of thought today if he had the chance to enjoy convenient access to knowledge in this century like you.</p><p><br></p><p>He\'d probably laugh you out of town for steadfastly holding to archaic ways of thinking as if they were gospel.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: 1st paragraph of your reply belittles the written works of Dr Carl Jung absent an intent to inquire on the article I bring forth.</p><p><br></p><p>2nd paragraph denotes your preference for logic and the mistrust for archaic knowledge.</p><p><br></p><p>3rd and 4th are an arrogant preposition that serves to belittle scholars articles.</p><p><br></p><p>To that end I believe this back and forth is pointless, to each their own elder.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike:&nbsp;Yeah, you had to trivialize my response.</p><p><br></p><p>Anyway, I was simply pointing out the fact that it\'s time to move forward and discard outdated, illogical ways of thinking if they can\'t stand scientific scrutiny. You and I have the benefit of hindsight and the tools to scientifically examine concepts and hypotheses so why not be critical and discerning when it comes to accepting ideas, however dated?</p><p><br></p><p>Dr. Jung\'s work isn\'t exempt from critical examination so if the premise of his writings on finding a nexus between science and the metaphysical realm isn\'t convincing enough, how\'s it sensible to cling to them? After all alchemy, which he was a major proponent of is nothing but pseudoscience. I\'m not trying to take anything away from him.</p><p><br></p><p>If we don\'t question what these old disciplines teach, then we\'re perpetuating outdated, potentially harmful beliefs. I\'m inviting you, @kaynety, @SonOfTheSoil and co to be open-minded and welcome the habit of asking questions. Challenge assumptions and embrace empirical evidence. That\'s what science is all about.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: In the spirit of being open minded and asking questions, I have a final one. What is your scientific opinion on dreams? </p><p><br></p><p>Mike: I\'m no expert in neuroscience but the little I know is that dreams are an avenue for the human brain to consolidate memories and help in the problem-solving of complex thoughts. What does your camp have to say about them?</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: Plenty about the subconscious and it\'s mode of communication to the ego or the conscious mind.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike: Would that hold up to scientific scrutiny through such tools as neurochemistry? Would it be verifiable? Also, animals have been shown to dream, just like humans. Do animals have a subconscious ergo a conscious mind and ego?</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: I haven\'t had the time to inquire from the animals I own, however when you said dreams aid in complex problem solving how is that any different from your subconscious communicating to your conscious?</p><p><br></p><p>Mike: For starters, one is a process of the brain that is observable and measurable scientifically, while the other is still a matter of speculation. Neurochemistry has been used to map the brain\'s activities during sleep and interpret what the dreamer was experiencing. That lends a lot more credibility to my hypothesis than your yet-to-be-verified (and almost unverifiable) theories.</p><p><br></p><p>Also, do not confound wakefulness with consciousness.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: You seem knowledgeable in neurochemistry, so tell me more about this measurable tool, does it map out the brain activity to the point it displays the images in the dream?</p><p><br></p><p>Don\'t claim ownership over an already developed hypothesis!</p><p><br></p><p>Mike: LOL. Calm down. Maybe I should have said \"our\" hypothesis to mean we of rational thinking.</p><p><br></p><p>To your question on measurement, I am under no obligation to answer that as it neighbours the trivial and ridiculous.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: So you\'ve ran out of smart arse answers have you?</p><p><br></p><p>It\'s a simple question not a trivial nor ridiculous one as the whole point of dreams is the content which ought to entail both the material and the subjects reactions, so does the machine record the actual dreams or does it not?</p><p><br></p><p>Mike: Oh, I\'m sure I can come up with a few more smart-alecky answers.</p><p><br></p><p>But wait, no, I don\'t have to. Anyhow, to the best of my knowledge, it doesn\'t actually record a person\'s dreams. What it does is measure brain activity, eye movements and the like which provide clues and insights into the dreaming process. EEGs, for example, can measure electrical signals in the brain while PET scans measure blood flow in parts of the brain associated with dreaming. It\'s a work in progress and if you don\'t want to understand that, you\'re a moron.</p><p><br></p><p>Now, quit deflections and ask a sensible question.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: I already asked my question on the images and the short answer is no, it cannot!</p><p>The machine in all it\'s splendor does not record images experienced in the dream and that is what the good doctor and his peers attempted to interpret what the images, and more importantly their symbology attempt to communicate to the conscious mind.</p><p><br></p><p>For example, there\'s one common dream about soaring through the air, and upon the dreamers realization of flight, he/she tends to fall down no longer capable of the feat.</p><p><br></p><p>What does the ability of flight mean to the subject?</p><p><br></p><p>Why is he/she capable of realizing they can fly?</p><p><br></p><p>Why does he/she fall?</p><p><br></p><p>Each individual has their own psyche so dreams and more importantly their CONTENTS so each and every single dream is unique as well as the patterns within it.</p><p><br></p><p>The whole point is symbology, and symbols especially old ones have never been restrained by language, there have an deeper meaning, barely seen on the surface.</p><p><br></p><p>It\'s a new year oh rational one, include poetry in your life not insults!</p><p><br></p><p>Mike: LOL.</p><p>I\'m not even sure what you\'ve typed is poetic,</p><p>Neither am I sure it was a sarcastic dig or polemic,</p><p>Perhaps a frantic attempt to make the olden seem more charismatic,</p><p>But I\'m sure it was anything but epic or scientific,</p><p>And it\'s actually something I\'d expect from a manic schizophrenic.</p><p><br></p><p>I\'m serving you poetic insults in case it\'s not clear,</p><p>Because I\'m all for vawulence anytime of the year,</p><p>Now, you can keep dreaming up myths and theories,</p><p>But reality is what we need to make everything in life clear.</p><p><br></p><p>Your outdated beliefs over time have been reduced to shite,</p><p>So get your head out of your aㅤss, and open your eyes to the light.</p><p><br></p><p>By the way, your attempts at sarcasm are nothing but farce,</p><p>And your attempts at logic have been left in arrears,</p><p>The ancient symbols you cling to have no place in this age,</p><p>Your ancient thinking should be locked away in a cage,</p><p>No matter how hard you try to make it sound sage.</p><p><br></p><p>All said, your stubbornness is an affront to this century\'s logic,</p><p>Bukowski, Jung and Freud would agree,</p><p>That you should give up your ancient ways and be free,</p><p>And never again should you try to argue with me,</p><p>And never again should you try to be so iconic through poetry.</p><p><br></p><p>Back to the content of dreams, the general understanding is that flight usually symbolizes freedom and liberation, while falling down denotes a fear of failure or being overwhelmed. It can also represent a fear of success or a desire to be grounded.</p><p><br></p><p>While there are some common themes, as you mentioned, each dream is unique and can only be interpreted by the dreamer themselves. Symbols can represent a range of different things and often have multiple layers of meaning. Science has no explanation yet</p><p><br></p><p>The interpretation of the symbols in dreams can be subjective but as I said before, it should be open to critical examination and scientific inquiry and that\'s why I said it\'s a moot point trying to marry science and superstition. Superstition shouldn\'t begin where science is at a loss or yet to come up with an explanation. Logic should tell you so.</p><p><br></p><p>I\'m not sure how I got to writing rhyming poetry or why I even got down this rabbit hole with you. Nevertheless, I\'d like to remind you that my point is that if we don\'t critically examine what these old disciplines teach, we\'re just perpetuating archaic beliefs that have nothing to offer humanity besides wishful thinking and delusional solutions.</p><p><br></p><p>So if there\'s no new reasonable question, it\'s time to move on my friend.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: I actually did a paper last year, a Master, about neuromarketing. It was, and it is, to my understanding that tools such as EEGs are specifically used to denote a person\'s interests, at least in the marketing context. The tool will measure an individual\'s brain activity when subjected to a specific phenomenon. I am struggling to understand how that applies to dreams and just how exactly researchers discern what was covered in the dream.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike:&nbsp;</p><p>EEGs can measure brain activity in sleep,</p><p>And link it to certain dream states however deep,</p><p>The idea behind that is emotions can be found,</p><p>Through brain activity, eye movements all around,</p><p>And contraction of facial muscles that abound.</p><p><br></p><p>They can\'t directly record the dream sequence,</p><p>But by asking subjects what was experienced,</p><p>Scientists can link it to brain measurements,</p><p>And infer the dream\'s nature from the facial expressions,</p><p><br></p><p>To you Brian resident of Githurai 44 I must say,</p><p>Be critical and ask questions to what people like Jung say,</p><p>Challenge assumptions and embrace empirical evidence,</p><p>So that you will be spared the shame of being naive</p><p><br></p><p>The interpretation of the dream\'s content,</p><p>And symbols is very subjective in intent,</p><p>Which makes it easy to be taken in by claims,</p><p>That are baseless and rooted in wishful thinking, not facts.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: And to you Mike I retort, that besides 44 actually being a pretty decent neighborhood to reside in, the patterns within the fields of the subconscious are abstract and thus can be considered a qualitative variable and not quantitative, and while gadgets and their flashy gizmos impressive as they are have yet to scan images therein.</p><p><br></p><p>Dr Jung laid down the premises of the contested by the um..shall we say rationalists, of the ego and the subconscious. This has brought about in occultic leaning cartoons the aspect of a protagonist whilst in a dilemma and angel popping on one shoulder advising caution while a devil popping on the other advising throwing caution to the wind, countless series bear the same blueprint of a holy vs a rubble rousing friend and this is by design.</p><p><br></p><p>As far as naivety goes, it takes a special sort of stupid for a man to discard knowledge in the name of being archaic and outdated, while better men than you have sought to consolidate the importance of symbolism in this modern world.</p><p><br></p><p>I gave an example of the Qatari world cup insignia bearing the resemblance of Ourubus, a snake devouring it\'s own tail.</p><p><br></p><p>Another I\'ll provide is primitive tribes preference to exemplify a virtue by an animal, Kings in Africa preferring lions and leopard skins, Kings in Europe preference for Wolf and bear fur, stone age paintings of animals found deep in caves, Ancient Egyptians with Seth..and tons more.</p><p><br></p><p>Unlike you I don\'t pout my bony chest out and proclaim that certain works of esteemed mind are nonsense nor hoist my skirts up and turn my nose on knowledge because it predates the first time I burst a nut.</p><p><br></p><p>I intend to dedicate a huge chunk of 2023 to study subjective symbols, and if that earns me shame of naivety then so be it, society as is stands currently is full of sh\'t anyway.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike:</p><p>When you put words in my mouth like that,</p><p>it takes to reason that you be taken to task,</p><p>For I never said that Jung\'s works were nonsense,</p><p>only that they should be subjected to rigors of modern science.</p><p><br></p><p>Your type have the tendency to see shadows in the dark,</p><p>when the light of logic and reason can illuminate your heart,</p><p>Your case in point of the Qatar insignia,</p><p>is no proof that superstition should not be questioned,</p><p>As for stone age paintings and ancient Egyptians,</p><p>They are part of history,</p><p>not the present day equation.</p><p>Cause and coincidence are not to be confounded,</p><p>And I\'m afraid your approach precludes further discourse along that course.</p><p><br></p><p>The interpretation of symbols depends on the individual,</p><p>Which is why it\'s imperative to be critical and question them in a scientific way,</p><p>So that the truth is revealed and not what we want to hear.</p><p><