ientific approach to education as you.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike: Catch me dead trying to marry a school of thought that speaks of \"merging the left and right spheres of the mind\" with logic and science. It just sounds like a lazy, desperate effort to make your old, outdated beliefs sound more credible. Yours is a moot point if not an effort in futility my friend.</p><p><br></p><p>If your superstitions were presented in a more critical light, I wouldn\'t be so dismissive. There\'s simply no place for superstitions anymore. Anything put forward is subject to the rigors of scientific examination, no matter how venerable the source. Even the most respected figures can be wrong or have their own biases and limitations.</p><p><br></p><p>We\'ve actually made leaps and bounds since Jung put forward his propositions, and I\'m more than certain he would belong to a different school of thought today if he had the chance to enjoy convenient access to knowledge in this century like you.</p><p><br></p><p>He\'d probably laugh you out of town for steadfastly holding to archaic ways of thinking as if they were gospel.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: 1st paragraph of your reply belittles the written works of Dr Carl Jung absent an intent to inquire on the article I bring forth.</p><p><br></p><p>2nd paragraph denotes your preference for logic and the mistrust for archaic knowledge.</p><p><br></p><p>3rd and 4th are an arrogant preposition that serves to belittle scholars articles.</p><p><br></p><p>To that end I believe this back and forth is pointless, to each their own elder.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike:&nbsp;Yeah, you had to trivialize my response.</p><p><br></p><p>Anyway, I was simply pointing out the fact that it\'s time to move forward and discard outdated, illogical ways of thinking if they can\'t stand scientific scrutiny. You and I have the benefit of hindsight and the tools to scientifically examine concepts and hypotheses so why not be critical and discerning when it comes to accepting ideas,