ukowski, Jung and Freud would agree,</p><p>That you should give up your ancient ways and be free,</p><p>And never again should you try to argue with me,</p><p>And never again should you try to be so iconic through poetry.</p><p><br></p><p>Back to the content of dreams, the general understanding is that flight usually symbolizes freedom and liberation, while falling down denotes a fear of failure or being overwhelmed. It can also represent a fear of success or a desire to be grounded.</p><p><br></p><p>While there are some common themes, as you mentioned, each dream is unique and can only be interpreted by the dreamer themselves. Symbols can represent a range of different things and often have multiple layers of meaning. Science has no explanation yet</p><p><br></p><p>The interpretation of the symbols in dreams can be subjective but as I said before, it should be open to critical examination and scientific inquiry and that\'s why I said it\'s a moot point trying to marry science and superstition. Superstition shouldn\'t begin where science is at a loss or yet to come up with an explanation. Logic should tell you so.</p><p><br></p><p>I\'m not sure how I got to writing rhyming poetry or why I even got down this rabbit hole with you. Nevertheless, I\'d like to remind you that my point is that if we don\'t critically examine what these old disciplines teach, we\'re just perpetuating archaic beliefs that have nothing to offer humanity besides wishful thinking and delusional solutions.</p><p><br></p><p>So if there\'s no new reasonable question, it\'s time to move on my friend.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: I actually did a paper last year, a Master, about neuromarketing. It was, and it is, to my understanding that tools such as EEGs are specifically used to denote a person\'s interests, at least in the marketing context. The tool will measure an individual\'s brain activity when subjected to a specific phenomenon. I am struggling to understand how that applies to dreams and just how exactly researchers discern what was covered in the dream.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike:&nbsp;</p><p>EEGs can measure brain activity in sleep,</p><p>And link it to certain dream states however deep,</p><p>The idea behind that is emotions can be found,</p><p>Through brain activity, eye movements all around,</p><p>And contraction of facial muscles that abound.</p><p><br></p><p>They can\'t directly record the dream sequence,</p><p>But by asking subjects what was experienced,</p><p>Scientists can link it to brain measurements,</p><p>And infer the dream\'s nature from the facial expressions,</p><p><br></p><p>To you Brian resident of Githurai 44 I must say,</p><p>Be critical and ask questions to what people like Jung say,</p><p>Challenge assumptions and embrace empirical evidence,</p><p>So that you will be spared the shame of being naive</p><p><br></p><p>The interpretation of the dream\'s content,</p><p>And symbols is very subjective in intent,</p><p>Which makes it easy to be taken in by claims,</p><p>That are baseless and rooted in wishful thinking, not facts.</p><p><br></p><p>Jay: And to you Mike I retort, that besides 44 actually being a pretty decent neighborhood to reside in, the patterns within the fields of the subconscious are abstract and thus can be considered a qualitative variable and not quantitative, and while gadgets and their flashy gizmos impressive as they are have yet to scan images therein.</p><p><br></p><p>Dr Jung laid down the premises of the contested by the um..shall we say rationalists, of the ego and the subconscious. This has brought about in occultic leaning cartoons the aspect of a protagonist whilst in a dilemma and angel popping on one shoulder advising caution while a devil popping on the other advising throwing caution to the wind, countless series bear the same blueprint of a holy vs a rubble rousing friend and this is by design.</p><p><br></p><p>As far as naivety goes, it takes a special sort of stupid for a man to discard knowledge in the name of being archaic and outdated, while better men than you have sought to consolidate the importance of symbolism in this modern world.</p><p><br></p><p>I gave an example of the Qatari world cup insignia bearing the resemblance of Ourubus, a snake devouring it\'s own tail.</p><p><br></p><p>Another I\'ll provide is primitive tribes preference to exemplify a virtue by an animal, Kings in Africa preferring lions and leopard skins, Kings in Europe preference for Wolf and bear fur, stone age paintings of animals found deep in caves, Ancient Egyptians with Seth..and tons more.</p><p><br></p><p>Unlike you I don\'t pout my bony chest out and proclaim that certain works of esteemed mind are nonsense nor hoist my skirts up and turn my nose on knowledge because it predates the first time I burst a nut.</p><p><br></p><p>I intend to dedicate a huge chunk of 2023 to study subjective symbols, and if that earns me shame of naivety then so be it, society as is stands currently is full of sh\'t anyway.</p><p><br></p><p>Mike:</p><p>When you put words in my mouth like that,</p><p>it takes to reason that you be taken to task,</p><p>For I never said that Jung\'s works were nonsense,</p><p>only that they should be subjected to rigors of modern science.</p><p><br></p><p>Your type have the tendency to see shadows in the dark,</p><p>when the light of logic and reason can illuminate your heart,</p><p>Your case in point of the Qatar insignia,</p><p>is no proof that superstition should not be questioned,</p><p>As for stone age paintings and ancient Egyptians,</p><p>They are part of history,</p><p>not the present day equation.</p><p>Cause and coincidence are not to be confounded,</p><p>And I\'m afraid your approach precludes further discourse along that course.</p><p><br></p><p>The interpretation of symbols depends on the individual,</p><p>Which is why it\'s imperative to be critical and question them in a scientific way,</p><p>So that the truth is revealed and not what we want to hear.</p><p><br></p><p>Symbols have their place in the modern world,</p><p>But the interpretation must be able to be unfurled,</p><p>It\'s no longer acceptable to take them at face value,</p><p>We must be critical and question, that\'s the rational we must solve.</p><p><br></p><p>As for naivety, it takes a special kind of irrational boldness,</p><p>To cling to superstition and ignore scientific evidence,</p><p>Without questioning the validity of its source,</p><p>And calling it a day without any recourse.</p><p><br></p><p>You\'re something of a clod,</p><p>If you don\'t have the courage to be critical of what these old disciplines teach,</p><p>Do not be ashamed of your naivety,</p><p>But instead strive for veritable knowledge that\'s rooted in logic!</p><p>So, when it comes to ancient ways of thinking,</p><p>Don\'t be afraid to challenge assumptions,</p><p>And embrace empirical evidence for solutions.</p><p><br></p><p>Otherwise, if dedicating time to studying symbols is what you choose,</p><p>I\'d suggest you arm yourself with knowledge and facts,</p><p>And be open to critical examination and scientific inquiry.</p><p>So don\'t be afraid to ask questions,</p><p>And use science to prove the assertions,</p><p>For the future is here, and it\'s time to move on.</p><p><br></p><p>Your a priori argument is a fallacy, if not a fallacy of logic,</p><p>So it\'s time to break away from symbols and mythic,</p><p>And embrace the modern world with its science and logic,</p><p>And leave the old ways behind, where they belong,</p><p>In the realm of myth and superstition,</p><p>Now, where do I claim compensation for bearing your incoherent retort?</p></div><div class=\"ql-clipboard\" tabindex=\"-1\" contenteditable=\"true\"></div><div class=\"ql-tooltip ql-hidden\"><a class=\"ql-preview\" target=\"_blank\" href=\"blank\" rel=\"noopener\"></a><input type=\"text\" data-formula=\"e=mc^2\" data-link=\"https://quilljs.com\" data-video=\"Embed URL\"><a class=\"ql-action\"></a><a class=\"ql-remove\"></